[ChapterName "Carlsen's Unusual 3...a6!?"]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/GDUwm3BB/F3VH1wH5"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/EricRosen"]

1. d4 d5 2. c4 e6 3. Nf3 (3. Nc3 a6!? { also playable for black }) 3... a6 { Sigmav asks: Why did black play a6 ? What is the idea behind a6 ? } 4. e3 (4. Nc3 dxc4 { A nice version of the QGA where a6 is quite useful } 5. e4 b5 6. a4 b4 7. Ne2 c5) (4. cxd5 { The most principled move, but helps black unleash the light-squared bishop } { [%csl Ra6] } 4... exd5 5. Nc3 c6 { Aronian, L. - Carlsen, M., 0-1, 4th Norway Blitz 2016, https://lichess.org/RgIL2Hr2 } { [%csl Gd5,Gd6,Gc8][%cal Gf8d6,Gg8e7,Ge8g8,Gc8e6,Gd8c7,Gb8d7,Gd7f6,Gc8f5] } 6. Bf4 Bd6 7. Bxd6 Qxd6 8. e3 Ne7 9. Bd3 Bf5 { With a balanced position }) (4. c5?! b6 5. b4 a5 { [%csl Gc5,Gb6,Ga5] }) 4... Nf6 5. Nc3 dxc4 6. Bxc4 b5 7. Be2 Bb7 8. O-O Nbd7 9. Bd2 Bd6 { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gc7c5,Ge6e5] } 10. Rc1 O-O 11. Qe1 { [%csl Ga5][%cal Gd2a5] } 11... Qe7 12. Nb1 e5 13. Ba5 exd4 14. Nxd4 Qe5 { [%csl Rh2,Rb2] } 15. g3 c5 16. Bf3 Bxf3 17. Nxf3 Qxb2 18. e4 Rfe8 19. Bc3 Qxa2 20. e5 Qd5 { [%csl Re5,Rf3][%cal Ge8e1] } 21. Qd1 Qxd1 22. Rfxd1 Bxe5 { 0-1 White resigns. } { https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=rXqXGlWjslI } 0-1


[Event "Answering Questions: Meeting the \"Anti-London\""]
[Date "2018.09.26"]
[Result "*"]
[Variant "Standard"]
[ECO "A43"]
[Opening "Benoni Defense: Benoni Gambit Accepted"]
[StudyName "Answering Questions"]
[ChapterName "Meeting the \"Anti-London\""]
[ChapterURL "https://lichess.org/study/GDUwm3BB/3XzvXNV8"]
[Annotator "https://lichess.org/@/EricRosen"]
[UTCDate "2018.09.26"]
[UTCTime "17:44:09"]

{ From Chet Heflin: "Eric Rosen has a dvd series on the London. I watched his advertisement, watched him play the London on numerous occasions. Very excited to purchase his London DVD at the first of the month. Anyway, it’s killing me to find out how Eric meets 1...c5. At my chess club, after 1.d4, a NM played 1...c5, The Old Benoni. I played 2.c3 and lost the b2 pawn after 1.d4 c5 2.c3 d6 3.Bf4 cxd4 4.cxd4 Qb6 - and now Qb6 attacks both d4 and b2. I played 5.e3, then he played 5...Qxb2. I learned afterwards that I could have played 5.Qc2, and if Black plays 5...Qxd4?? , White has Qxc8+. GM Simon Williams teaches 1.d4 c5 2.d5, and 1.d4 Nf6 2.Bf4 c5 3.d5. What concerns me is what to do if Black plays a move in the Czech Benoni, 1d4 c5 2.d5 e5. Now Bf4 may not be a good move, 1.d4 c5 2.d5 e5 3.dxe5ep fxe6 4.Bf4 (?). So Eric, do you play 1.d4 c5 2.d5, or 1.d4 c5 2.c3? And if you play 2.d5, what do you play after 2...e5? Thanks! Looking forward to your DVD on the London next month.﻿" }
1. d4 c5 2. dxc5!? { A tricky variation, and my recommendation for many players } (2. d5 { The most principled and objectively the best move. The game will now enter some kind of Benoni Structure (denoted by black's pawn on c5, and white's pawn on d5) } 2... e5 3. e4 { [%csl Gb5,Gd5,Ge4,Rf1][%cal Gf1b5,Gb1c3,Gg1f3,Gf3d2,Gd2c4,Ga2a4,Rb7b5] } 3... d6 4. Nc3 Be7 5. Bb5+ Nd7 { Akobian, Varuzhan - Tate, Emory, 1-0, Western States op, 2004, https://lichess.org/R21WgQuo }) (2. c3 cxd4 3. cxd4) 2... e6 { [%cal Gb1c3,Gc3e4] } 3. Nc3 Bxc5 4. Ne4 { [%csl Rc5,Rd6] } 4... Be7?! { The most common move (according to the lichess database), but not the best } (4... d5 5. Nxc5 Qa5+ 6. c3 Qxc5 7. e4! $14 Nf6 (7... dxe4 8. Qg4! { Danielian, Elina - Arakhamia Grant, Ketevan, 1-0, ROM-chT (Women), 2009, https://lichess.org/D5jtHVc8 } { [%csl Ge4,Gg7] }) 8. e5 Nfd7 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. Bf4 O-O 11. Bd3 { [%cal Gd3h7,Gf3g5] }) (4... Nf6! 5. Nxc5 Qa5+ 6. c3 Qxc5 7. g3 d5 8. Bg2 O-O 9. Nf3 Nc6 10. O-O e5 11. Bg5 { [%cal Gg5f6] } 11... Ne4 12. Be3) 5. Nd6+ Bxd6 6. Qxd6 $14 { Very pleasant position for white! } { [%csl Gd6][%cal Gc1f4,Ge1c1] } *


